This spontaneous report was received from a consumer and concerns a 10-month-old female patient from the 
United States: 017542769A.
The patient's height was not reported and weight was 18 pounds. The patient's concurrent condition included ear 
infection.
The patient was treated with paracetamol (suspension, oral) 2.5 ml as needed initiated on an unspecified date for 
teething and ear infection. Concomitant medications were not reported.
On an unspecified date, the patient was given the product for teething and ear infection and her parents realized 
that they were not shaking the bottle of paracetamol before use and the product did not work (drug ineffective for 
unapproved indication, off label use and did not shake the bottle/wrong technique in drug usage process). It was 
reported that the parents of the patient threw the product as they realized that they did not shake the bottle.
The outcome for did not shake the bottle/wrong technique in drug usage process, off label use and drug ineffective 
for unapproved indication was not reported.
The dose of paracetamol was not changed.
This report was not serious.
